Tierra Whack, originally known as Dizzle Dizz, is an American rapper from Philadelphia, PA.

She debuted in 2018 with the audiovisual album Whack World.

Growing artistically in Philly’s battle rap scene, her main musical influences are Lauryn Hill, André 3000, Eminem, Missy Elliott, and Busta Rhymes.

songs.title: Unemployed

description.plain:
“Unemployed” is the fifth weekly single released by Tierra Whack since the release of “Only Child” on February 19, 2019, as part of a series labelled #whackhistorymonth. It was also announced on Instagram.
https://www.instagram.com/p/BvMiBQ4ny3_/
The track is generally confrontational and self-affirming against those that Tierra may classify as her enemies.

She said “the cover art is a potato on a couch. So a couch potato”. Tierra did this because people who are “unemployed” can be seen as “couch potatoes”. She also took this idea to the extreme in her video to create a theme as discussed below.

The official music video for the song has been uploaded on April 10, 2019 on YouTube, after it had been officially previewed on Cartoon Network, during an episode of the series Samurai Jack: it is really reminiscent of the strange and sometimes nightmarish series of clips for the Whack World project, and it features Tierra as a cook (or, better saying, a “potato murderer”) for… two giant and alive potatoes!

songs.title: MUMBO JUMBO

description.plain:
This song is called “Mumbo Jumbo” because there actually aren’t official lyrics. Tierra explains in a Pigeons and Planes interview: “When I’m recording, I usually just mumble and hum a melody and then fill the words in as I go. This time I just decided not to.”

She also mentions she went to the dentist the same week she recorded this song, which inspired the video. This might relate to the lyrics as well, because after you get a tooth pulled, this is basically what you sound like. She uses similar imagery in the video for “Bug’s Life” on “Whack World,” in which her face is swollen as if she just had a tooth pulled.

Thanks to this single, Tierra received a nomination for Best Music Video for the 2019 Grammy Awards, eventually being beaten by Childish Gambino’s “This Is America”.

songs.title: Only Child

description.plain:
“Only Child” is Tierra Whack’s first release since 2018’s Whack World, and the first track in her “Whack History Month” series.

The Nick Verruto and KVYREN produced song is a smooth four-minute cut where the Philly artist alternates between singing and laying down bars.

“Only Child” comes less than a month after J. Cole’s “MIDDLE CHILD,” and while the subject matter doesn’t seem to correlate to the North Carolina native’s song, the two songs do have several connections. “Only Child” is Whack’s first release since her deal with Interscope/Universal Music Group, who J. Cole is also tied to, the covers both feature static, and Martin “PoorMarty” Perry was enlisted for the animation for both of the songs audio videos.

On the 20th. Aug, a ‘'Screen Visualizer’‘ video by Thibaut Duverneix of Gentilhomme was uploaded to YouTube as part of #WhackHistoryMonth.

Body Of Water is the lead single from Philadelphia rapper Tierra Whack’s first release of 2022, Pop?. The 3-track Extended Play also features songs Lazy and Dolly.

The track is flooded with many references in its trap-influenced beat, from a direct reference to Drake, to a coronavirus reference in the chorus reading, “Taking over like a virus”. Many themes in the song also tackle things such as free love, anti-racism, and world positivity.

Tierra has been everywhere on social media promoting the lead single, with a music video, BTS (Behind The Scenes) video, and she also said this to Genius Verified this week,

“Body Of Water” is [actually] five years old. I remember I was listening to OutKast, and I’m still listening to them to this day, and I just wanted something so powerful, like rockstar, crazy big stage…"

songs.title: Pet Cemetery

description.plain:
Tierra uses “Pet Cemetery” as a tribute to her friend and fellow Philadelphia rapper, Hulitho, who passed away in 2016: he’s also briefly mentioned in “4 Wings,” another song from Whack World.

Throughout the one-minute song, Tierra repeatedly quotes the 1989 animated movie, All Dogs Go to Heaven, in which a German Shepherd, named Charlie B. Barkin, after getting murdered by a fellow dog and former friend, withdraws from his place in Heaven to return to Earth and seek revenge, but eventually desists from his original purpose thanks to the help from several key characters.

songs.title: Link

description.plain:
“Link” is a collaborative effort between Tierra Whack and Lego. Lyrically, the Philadelphia rapper encourages children to use their imagination and build Legos with her as part of the Lego “Rebuild the World” campaign.

The music video of the song was created with some help from a group of Philadelphia children as they brainstormed several ideas. In the video, Tierra builds a coyote-lizard spaceship with Legos and launches it into space. However, later, she couldn’t bear the loneliness and crashes the spaceship back down to earth.



The video marks the second collaboration between Tierra and director Cat Solen, following the music video of Tierra’s April 2019 song, “Unemployed.”

songs.title: Heaven

description.plain:
Over the somber and minimal instrumental for “Heaven,” Tierra Whack remembers the loved ones she lost during the years and has conversations with God, even making a reference to John Newton’s historical hymn “Amazing Grace,” which is frequently sung at funerals and memorial services.

While Tierra hasn’t still touched religious themes so frequently throughout her discography, with actual examples being “Only Child” and Flying Lotus’s “Yellow Belly,” the loss of close friends has actually been at the core of some of her songs: this is specifically true for “4 Wings” and “Pet Cemetery,” two songs from her 2018 album Whack World, where she paid tribute to her late friend and fellow rapper Hulitho.

songs.title: Story to tell

description.plain:
On “Story to tell,” rising Philadelphia female rapper Tierra Whack details her newfound rise to fame and how she got involved with the We Run the Streets collective.

The single interpolates The Notorious B.I.G.’s 1997 track “I Got a Story to Tell.” Whack, who went by Dizzle Dizz at the time, is a huge fan of Biggie, as seen by her shirt in the music video which depicts B.I.G.’s debut studio album, Ready to Die.
